work, and play within a single structure. Mall City features Hong Kong as a unique rendering of an advanced consumer society. Retail space has come a long way since the nineteenth-century covered passages of Paris, which once awed the bourgeoisie with glass roofs and gaslights. It has morphed from the arcade to the department store, and from the mall into the “mall city”—where “expresscalators” crisscross mesmerizing atriums. Highlighting the effects of this development in Hong Kong, this book raises questions about architecture, city planning, culture, and urban life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aAl, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCartier, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartier, Carolyn.1 aChu, Cecilia L.1 aChu, Cecilia L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Tung-Yiu Stan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Tung-Yiu Stan.1 aMathews, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathews, Gordon.1 aNowek, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNowek, Adam.1 aShane, David Grahame, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShane, David Grahame.1 aShelton, Barrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShelton, Barrie.1 aSolomon, Jonathan D.1 aSolomon, Jonathan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311065811840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485544440uhttps://www.degruyter.com